{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01325S8iHHAj7QDRBBjHQaKx","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# `bob_tools.planfile`: deterministic PLAN.md handling\n2\t\n3\tStatus: draft for discussion. Scope: define a single library that owns\n4\tPLAN.md syntax, parsing, serialization, and operations across McLoop,\n5\tDuplo, and human editors, so that PLAN.md handling stops being\n6\tLLM-mediated and starts being deterministic.\n7\t\n8\tThis document is structured for cold review. Every claim about\n9\texisting behavior cites the file and function it was verified against.\n10\tEvery proposed addition is marked as such. Open questions are flagged\n11\texplicitly at the end.\n12\t\n13\t---\n14\t\n15\t## 1. Problem\n16\t\n17\tPLAN.md is currently produced, parsed, and mutated by three actors:\n18\tMcLoop's runner, Duplo's planner, and humans editing directly.\n19\tMcLoop has a real parser\n20\t(`mcloop/checklist.py:parse`, line 151); Duplo writes through an\n21\tLLM and a partial postprocess; humans edit freely. The three actors\n22\tdo not share a single contract, and the LLM-mediated paths have\n23\tproduced corruption that McLoop's parser explicitly refuses to\n24\tauto-fix (`PlanCorruptionError`, `mcloop/checklist.py:27`; the\n25\tfail-closed message is assembled at lines 142-148).\n26\t\n27\tThe goal is to make PLAN.md handling deterministic without removing\n28\tthe human-editable property. Concretely:\n29\t\n30\t- One library owns parsing, serialization, validation, and operations.\n31\t- McLoop and Duplo call the library; the LLM never owns plan structure.\n32\t- Humans may still hand-edit, but tools refuse to \"best-effort\" parse\n33\t  malformed input. Errors are line/column-located.\n34\t- The library coexists with the Plan Ledger\n35\t  (`bob_tools/ledger/`); it is not a replacement for the audit/event\n36\t  surface that already exists.\n37\t\n38\t## 2. Current state (audit)\n39\t\n40\tThis section records what is already on disk, with citations, so the\n41\tdesign does not invent state that already exists or contradict\n42\tbehavior that the runner depends on.\n43\t\n44\t### 2.1 McLoop's parser\n45\t\n46\t`mcloop/checklist.py` is the working parser. It defines:\n47\t\n48\t- `CHECKBOX_RE = r\"^(\\s*)- \\[([ xX!])\\] (.+)$\"` (line 9). Four markers\n49\t  are admitted: space (todo), `x`/`X` (done), `!` (failed).\n50\t- `STAGE_RE = r\"^#+\\s+.*?\\b(?:stage|phase)\\s+(\\d+)\\b\"` (line 12). Any\n51\t  heading level whose title contains `Stage N` or `Phase N` is a\n52\t  section header. The `\\d+` is mandatory — bare digits only.\n53\t- `BUGS_RE = r\"^#+\\s+Bugs\\s*$\"` (line 14). Any heading level titled\n54\t  exactly `Bugs` is the bug-priority section.\n55\t- Four operational tags: `[USER]` (`_USER_TAG`, line 22),\n56\t  `[BATCH]` (`_BATCH_TAG`, line 23), `[AUTO:<action>]`\n57\t  (`_AUTO_TAG_RE`, line 24), and `[RULEDOUT]` as a non-task\n58\t  indent-attached line (handled in `parse`, lines 189-204).\n59\t- `PlanCorruptionError` (line 27) is raised on duplicate H1 titles,\n60\t  multiple `## Bugs` sections, or duplicate phase/stage numbers.\n61\t  Auto-fixing is deliberately not attempted (the docstring at line\n62\t  26 records the rationale).\n63\t\n64\tThe status enum is **three-valued**: `[ ] / [x] / [!]`. The `[USER]`\n65\ttoken is an orthogonal in-text tag, not a checkbox state.\n66\t`is_user_task` (line 627) substring-searches the task text.\n67\t\n68\t### 2.2 McLoop's execution semantics\n69\t\n70\t`mcloop/main.py:run_loop` consumes the parsed tree and dispatches on\n71\tthe tags:\n72\t\n73\t- `[AUTO:<action>]` tasks call `_handle_auto_task(label, action, args)`\n74\t  and are checked off automatically. The action vocabulary\n75\t  (`run_cli`, `run_gui`, `screenshot`, etc.) is interpreted by\n76\t  `mcloop/investigate_cmd.py`.\n77\t- `[USER]` tasks pause the run, print formatted instructions, and\n78\t  accept free-form text input. A failed `[USER]` verification files\n79\t  a new bug into BUGS.md and sets `terminal_failure`; the `[USER]`\n80\t  task itself stays unchecked for re-verification after the bug is\n81\t  fixed.\n82\t- `[BATCH]` parents collect consecutive unchecked children via\n83\t  `get_batch_children` (line 654) and run them as a single\n84\t  session. `[USER]` or `[AUTO:…]` children halt batch collection.\n85\t- `[RULEDOUT]` lines feed `get_eliminated(tasks, task)` whose result\n86\t  is appended to the task prompt as a \"RULED OUT APPROACHES\" block,\n87\t  suppressing repeat strategies (verified in\n88\t  `mcloop/runner.py`, lines 376-385, 422-431, and 482-491).\n89\t\n90\t`find_next` (line 434) implements the actionable-task algorithm:\n91\t\n92\t1. Bug tasks (under `## Bugs`) have absolute priority.\n93\t2. Otherwise, only tasks in the first incomplete stage are returned.\n94\t3. Failed subtasks (`[!]`) block all later siblings under the same\n95\t   parent (implicit sequential dependency,\n96\t   `_search_tasks`, lines 369-376).\n97\t4. A failed child prevents parent completion\n98\t   (`_auto_check_parents`, lines 730-756).\n99\t5. Auto-check parent when all children are done.\n100\t\n101\t`clear_failed_markers` (line 593) resets `[!]` back to `[ ]` on\n102\t`--retry`, anchored to checkbox syntax so prose containing the\n103\tliteral `- [!]` is not corrupted (lines 607-610).\n104\t\n105\t### 2.3 The Plan Ledger\n106\t\n107\t`bob_tools/ledger/` is already shipped and integrated into McLoop:\n108\t\n109\t- `bob_tools/ledger/SCHEMA.md` defines the on-disk format\n110\t  (`PLAN.events.jsonl`, append-only, one JSON object per line,\n111\t  envelope with `event_id` UUIDv7, `seq`, `writer_id`, `run_id`,\n112\t  `payload`).\n113\t- `mcloop/main.py` imports from `mcloop.ledger_config`,\n114\t  `mcloop.ledger_emit`, `mcloop.ledger_pause` and calls\n115\t  `_ledger_settle(label, TaskOutcome(...))` after every task in\n116\t  the standard code-edit success/failure path. Exit code 5 is\n117\t  reserved for ledger-induced hard stops (`HardStop`, `main.py`,\n118\t  lines 218-244).\n119\t- `mcloop/ledger_config.py` gates the ledger with, in precedence\n120\t  order, CLI flags, `MCLOOP_NO_PLAN_LEDGER` /\n121\t  `MCLOOP_NO_AUTO_REAUTHOR`, `.orchestra/config.json`, and finally\n122\t  auto-detection of `<project>/.duplo/ledger/` (lines 1-17 and\n123\t  70-142).\n124\t- `mcloop/ledger_pause.py` evaluates thresholds after settlement and\n125\t  either returns no pause, invokes Duplo reauthor, or raises\n126\t  `HardStop`. It is explicitly fail-closed: failed reauthor leaves\n127\t  PLAN.md unchanged and records only the triggering crossing on the\n128\t  ledger (lines 1-22 and 297-420). Planfile does not need a separate\n129\t  \"paused state\" check; the settle/evaluate path already owns that\n130\t  decision.\n131\t- The ledger's status model is **richer than the parser's**:\n132\t  `pending | active | completed | abandoned | superseded | split |\n133\t  merged | blocked | provisional` (SCHEMA.md \"Phase status enum\").\n134\t- `TaskOutcome` (in `mcloop/ledger_emit.py:TaskOutcome`) carries\n135\t  `success`, `abandoned`, `summary`, `changed_files`,\n136\t  `failure_kind`, `transcript_ref`. The `failure_kind` field\n137\t  records `\"commit_failed\"`, `\"max_retries_exceeded\"`, etc.\n138\t\n139\t### 2.4 Phase identity in the ledger today\n140\t\n141\t`mcloop/ledger_emit.py` resolves phase IDs from PLAN.md via two\n142\tregexes:\n143\t\n144\t```python\n145\t_PHASE_HEADER_RE = re.compile(\n146\t    r\"^##\\s+Phase\\s+(?P<id>[A-Za-z0-9_]+):\\s+(?P<title>.+?)\\s*$\"\n147\t)\n148\t_PHASE_ID_COMMENT_RE = re.compile(\n149\t    r\"<!--\\s*phase_id\\s*:\\s*(?P<id>[A-Za-z0-9_]+)\\s*-->\"\n150\t)\n151\t```\n152\t\n153\t`find_explicit_phase_id_for_task(plan_text, task_label)` iterates\n154\tline by line. A line matching `_PHASE_HEADER_RE` sets\n155\t`current_phase_id`. A line containing the `task_label` as a\n156\tsubstring returns the current `current_phase_id`. A line matching\n157\t`_PHASE_ID_COMMENT_RE` updates `current_phase_id` for subsequent\n158\ttasks.\n159\t\n160\t`resolve_phase_id(plan_path, task_label, ordinal_index)` implements\n161\tthe explicit-required / ordinal-degraded contract. When the\n162\texplicit lookup yields nothing, `ordinal_index` maps to the n-th\n163\tphase header found. When that path runs, `record_phase_id_fallback`\n164\tprints a stderr warning and emits a `finding_observed` event tagged\n165\t`degraded`.\n166\t\n167\t### 2.5 The format incompatibility\n168\t\n169\tMcLoop's `STAGE_RE` requires `\\bphase\\s+\\d+\\b` — bare digits after\n170\t\"phase\". The ledger's `_PHASE_HEADER_RE` accepts\n171\t`[A-Za-z0-9_]+` after \"Phase\". The following table shows what each\n172\theading produces:\n173\t\n174\t| Heading                                            | McLoop STAGE_RE     | Ledger header regex             |\n175\t|----------------------------------------------------|---------------------|---------------------------------|\n176\t| `## Phase 1: Core`                                 | matches (stage 1)   | matches, `phase_id=\"1\"`         |\n177\t| `## Phase phase_001: Core`                         | **does not match**  | matches, `phase_id=\"phase_001\"` |\n178\t| `## Stage 1: Core`                                 | matches (stage 1)   | does not match                  |\n179\t| `## Stage 1: Core` + `<!-- phase_id: phase_001 -->`| matches (stage 1)   | matches via comment             |\n180\t\n181\tOnly the dual-line form satisfies both regexes today **and**\n182\tdelivers a stable string phase_id distinct from the ordinal. The\n183\tsingle-heading `## Phase phase_001:` form breaks McLoop's stage\n184\tdetection.\n185\t\n186\tA second-order consequence: a hypothetical `## Phase 1: ...` heading\n187\twould match both regexes, but the ledger would derive\n188\t`phase_id=\"1\"` from it. The current Duplo PLAN.md uses H1 phase\n189\theadings (`# Phase 1: ...`), which McLoop's `STAGE_RE` accepts but\n190\tthe ledger header regex does not. In both cases, the stable-ID\n191\tmigration cost is one `<!-- phase_id: phase_NNN -->` line per phase,\n192\twith no rewrite of the visible heading.\n193\t\n194\t### 2.6 PLAN.md / ledger directionality\n195\t\n196\t`run_loop`'s success path calls `check_off(active_file, task)` to\n197\twrite `[x]` to PLAN.md *first*, then calls\n198\t`_ledger_settle(label, TaskOutcome(success=True, ...))` which emits\n199\ta `commit_landed` event as audit evidence of what PLAN.md already\n200\trecords. PLAN.md is the writable surface; the ledger is the\n201\tappend-only witness. Hand-edits flow PLAN.md → ledger, never the\n202\treverse.\n203\t\n204\t## 3. Architecture\n205\t\n206\t### 3.1 Library placement\n207\t\n208\t```\n209\tbob/\n210\t  bob_tools/\n211\t    ledger/       # already exists; owns events + projected state\n212\t    planfile/     # NEW; owns PLAN.md syntax + canonicalization\n213\t      model.py\n214\t      parser.py\n215\t      renderer.py\n216\t      operations.py\n217\t      fileio.py\n218\t      cli.py\n219\t      tests/\n220\t```\n221\t\n222\tThe two libraries are peers. They cross at exactly two values:\n223\t\n224\t- `phase_id`: written and read by `planfile` via headings and\n225\t  `<!-- phase_id: ... -->` comments; consumed by `ledger` in event\n226\t  payloads.\n227\t- `task_label`: computed by `planfile` from position and stable IDs;\n228\t  resolved to `phase_id` (and, when stable task IDs land, to\n229\t  `task_id`) by the McLoop settle hook.\n230\t\n231\t`mcloop.checklist` becomes a thin compatibility wrapper or\n232\tdisappears once callers migrate. `mcloop.plan_split` and Duplo's\n233\tplanner write through `planfile`.\n234\t\n235\t### 3.2 Function inventory (proposed)\n236\t\n237\tPure operations on typed objects:\n238\t\n239\t```\n240\tparse_plan(text)               -> Plan | PlanSyntaxError\n241\trender_plan(plan)              -> str\n242\tvalidate_plan(plan)            -> None | PlanValidationError\n243\tcanonicalize(text)             -> str\n244\tmigrate(plan)                  -> Plan\n245\tnext_tasks(plan, limit=1)      -> list[Task]\n246\tcomplete_task(plan, task_id, outcome=None) -> tuple[Plan, tuple[Settlement, ...]]\n247\tfail_task(plan, task_id, reason, outcome=None) -> tuple[Plan, tuple[Settlement, ...]]\n248\treset_task(plan, task_id)      -> tuple[Plan, tuple[Settlement, ...]]\n249\tadd_task(plan, phase_id, text, deps=(), parent_id=None) -> Plan\n250\treplace_phase(plan, phase_id, new_phase) -> Plan"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c0ad05b9-4ddd-4925-a04d-c46811d784c5","uuid":"90d197ed-d9d0-4ced-9f2e-180b91140273","timestamp":"2026-05-16T02:39:46.174Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/mhcoen/proj/bob/design/planfile.md","content":"# `bob_tools.planfile`: deterministic PLAN.md handling\n\nStatus: draft for discussion. Scope: define a single library that owns\nPLAN.md syntax, parsing, serialization, and operations across McLoop,\nDuplo, and human editors, so that PLAN.md handling stops being\nLLM-mediated and starts being deterministic.\n\nThis document is structured for cold review. Every claim about\nexisting behavior cites the file and function it was verified against.\nEvery proposed addition is marked as such. Open questions are flagged\nexplicitly at the end.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Problem\n\nPLAN.md is currently produced, parsed, and mutated by three actors:\nMcLoop's runner, Duplo's planner, and humans editing directly.\nMcLoop has a real parser\n(`mcloop/checklist.py:parse`, line 151); Duplo writes through an\nLLM and a partial postprocess; humans edit freely. The three actors\ndo not share a single contract, and the LLM-mediated paths have\nproduced corruption that McLoop's parser explicitly refuses to\nauto-fix (`PlanCorruptionError`, `mcloop/checklist.py:27`; the\nfail-closed message is assembled at lines 142-148).\n\nThe goal is to make PLAN.md handling deterministic without removing\nthe human-editable property. Concretely:\n\n- One library owns parsing, serialization, validation, and operations.\n- McLoop and Duplo call the library; the LLM never owns plan structure.\n- Humans may still hand-edit, but tools refuse to \"best-effort\" parse\n  malformed input. Errors are line/column-located.\n- The library coexists with the Plan Ledger\n  (`bob_tools/ledger/`); it is not a replacement for the audit/event\n  surface that already exists.\n\n## 2. Current state (audit)\n\nThis section records what is already on disk, with citations, so the\ndesign does not invent state that already exists or contradict\nbehavior that the runner depends on.\n\n### 2.1 McLoop's parser\n\n`mcloop/checklist.py` is the working parser. It defines:\n\n- `CHECKBOX_RE = r\"^(\\s*)- \\[([ xX!])\\] (.+)$\"` (line 9). Four markers\n  are admitted: space (todo), `x`/`X` (done), `!` (failed).\n- `STAGE_RE = r\"^#+\\s+.*?\\b(?:stage|phase)\\s+(\\d+)\\b\"` (line 12). Any\n  heading level whose title contains `Stage N` or `Phase N` is a\n  section header. The `\\d+` is mandatory — bare digits only.\n- `BUGS_RE = r\"^#+\\s+Bugs\\s*$\"` (line 14). Any heading level titled\n  exactly `Bugs` is the bug-priority section.\n- Four operational tags: `[USER]` (`_USER_TAG`, line 22),\n  `[BATCH]` (`_BATCH_TAG`, line 23), `[AUTO:<action>]`\n  (`_AUTO_TAG_RE`, line 24), and `[RULEDOUT]` as a non-task\n  indent-attached line (handled in `parse`, lines 189-204).\n- `PlanCorruptionError` (line 27) is raised on duplicate H1 titles,\n  multiple `## Bugs` sections, or duplicate phase/stage numbers.\n  Auto-fixing is deliberately not attempted (the docstring at line\n  26 records the rationale).\n\nThe status enum is **three-valued**: `[ ] / [x] / [!]`. The `[USER]`\ntoken is an orthogonal in-text tag, not a checkbox state.\n`is_user_task` (line 627) substring-searches the task text.\n\n### 2.2 McLoop's execution semantics\n\n`mcloop/main.py:run_loop` consumes the parsed tree and dispatches on\nthe tags:\n\n- `[AUTO:<action>]` tasks call `_handle_auto_task(label, action, args)`\n  and are checked off automatically. The action vocabulary\n  (`run_cli`, `run_gui`, `screenshot`, etc.) is interpreted by\n  `mcloop/investigate_cmd.py`.\n- `[USER]` tasks pause the run, print formatted instructions, and\n  accept free-form text input. A failed `[USER]` verification files\n  a new bug into BUGS.md and sets `terminal_failure`; the `[USER]`\n  task itself stays unchecked for re-verification after the bug is\n  fixed.\n- `[BATCH]` parents collect consecutive unchecked children via\n  `get_batch_children` (line 654) and run them as a single\n  session. `[USER]` or `[AUTO:…]` children halt batch collection.\n- `[RULEDOUT]` lines feed `get_eliminated(tasks, task)` whose result\n  is appended to the task prompt as a \"RULED OUT APPROACHES\" block,\n  suppressing repeat strategies (verified in\n  `mcloop/runner.py`, lines 376-385, 422-431, and 482-491).\n\n`find_next` (line 434) implements the actionable-task algorithm:\n\n1. Bug tasks (under `## Bugs`) have absolute priority.\n2. Otherwise, only tasks in the first incomplete stage are returned.\n3. Failed subtasks (`[!]`) block all later siblings under the same\n   parent (implicit sequential dependency,\n   `_search_tasks`, lines 369-376).\n4. A failed child prevents parent completion\n   (`_auto_check_parents`, lines 730-756).\n5. Auto-check parent when all children are done.\n\n`clear_failed_markers` (line 593) resets `[!]` back to `[ ]` on\n`--retry`, anchored to checkbox syntax so prose containing the\nliteral `- [!]` is not corrupted (lines 607-610).\n\n### 2.3 The Plan Ledger\n\n`bob_tools/ledger/` is already shipped and integrated into McLoop:\n\n- `bob_tools/ledger/SCHEMA.md` defines the on-disk format\n  (`PLAN.events.jsonl`, append-only, one JSON object per line,\n  envelope with `event_id` UUIDv7, `seq`, `writer_id`, `run_id`,\n  `payload`).\n- `mcloop/main.py` imports from `mcloop.ledger_config`,\n  `mcloop.ledger_emit`, `mcloop.ledger_pause` and calls\n  `_ledger_settle(label, TaskOutcome(...))` after every task in\n  the standard code-edit success/failure path. Exit code 5 is\n  reserved for ledger-induced hard stops (`HardStop`, `main.py`,\n  lines 218-244).\n- `mcloop/ledger_config.py` gates the ledger with, in precedence\n  order, CLI flags, `MCLOOP_NO_PLAN_LEDGER` /\n  `MCLOOP_NO_AUTO_REAUTHOR`, `.orchestra/config.json`, and finally\n  auto-detection of `<project>/.duplo/ledger/` (lines 1-17 and\n  70-142).\n- `mcloop/ledger_pause.py` evaluates thresholds after settlement and\n  either returns no pause, invokes Duplo reauthor, or raises\n  `HardStop`. It is explicitly fail-closed: failed reauthor leaves\n  PLAN.md unchanged and records only the triggering crossing on the\n  ledger (lines 1-22 and 297-420). Planfile does not need a separate\n  \"paused state\" check; the settle/evaluate path already owns that\n  decision.\n- The ledger's status model is **richer than the parser's**:\n  `pending | active | completed | abandoned | superseded | split |\n  merged | blocked | provisional` (SCHEMA.md \"Phase status enum\").\n- `TaskOutcome` (in `mcloop/ledger_emit.py:TaskOutcome`) carries\n  `success`, `abandoned`, `summary`, `changed_files`,\n  `failure_kind`, `transcript_ref`. The `failure_kind` field\n  records `\"commit_failed\"`, `\"max_retries_exceeded\"`, etc.\n\n### 2.4 Phase identity in the ledger today\n\n`mcloop/ledger_emit.py` resolves phase IDs from PLAN.md via two\nregexes:\n\n```python\n_PHASE_HEADER_RE = re.compile(\n    r\"^##\\s+Phase\\s+(?P<id>[A-Za-z0-9_]+):\\s+(?P<title>.+?)\\s*$\"\n)\n_PHASE_ID_COMMENT_RE = re.compile(\n    r\"<!--\\s*phase_id\\s*:\\s*(?P<id>[A-Za-z0-9_]+)\\s*-->\"\n)\n```\n\n`find_explicit_phase_id_for_task(plan_text, task_label)` iterates\nline by line. A line matching `_PHASE_HEADER_RE` sets\n`current_phase_id`. A line containing the `task_label` as a\nsubstring returns the current `current_phase_id`. A line matching\n`_PHASE_ID_COMMENT_RE` updates `current_phase_id` for subsequent\ntasks.\n\n`resolve_phase_id(plan_path, task_label, ordinal_index)` implements\nthe explicit-required / ordinal-degraded contract. When the\nexplicit lookup yields nothing, `ordinal_index` maps to the n-th\nphase header found. When that path runs, `record_phase_id_fallback`\nprints a stderr warning and emits a `finding_observed` event tagged\n`degraded`.\n\n### 2.5 The format incompatibility\n\nMcLoop's `STAGE_RE` requires `\\bphase\\s+\\d+\\b` — bare digits after\n\"phase\". The ledger's `_PHASE_HEADER_RE` accepts\n`[A-Za-z0-9_]+` after \"Phase\". The following table shows what each\nheading produces:\n\n| Heading                                            | McLoop STAGE_RE     | Ledger header regex             |\n|----------------------------------------------------|---------------------|---------------------------------|\n| `## Phase 1: Core`                                 | matches (stage 1)   | matches, `phase_id=\"1\"`         |\n| `## Phase phase_001: Core`                         | **does not match**  | matches, `phase_id=\"phase_001\"` |\n| `## Stage 1: Core`                                 | matches (stage 1)   | does not match                  |\n| `## Stage 1: Core` + `<!-- phase_id: phase_001 -->`| matches (stage 1)   | matches via comment             |\n\nOnly the dual-line form satisfies both regexes today **and**\ndelivers a stable string phase_id distinct from the ordinal. The\nsingle-heading `## Phase phase_001:` form breaks McLoop's stage\ndetection.\n\nA second-order consequence: a hypothetical `## Phase 1: ...` heading\nwould match both regexes, but the ledger would derive\n`phase_id=\"1\"` from it. The current Duplo PLAN.md uses H1 phase\nheadings (`# Phase 1: ...`), which McLoop's `STAGE_RE` accepts but\nthe ledger header regex does not. In both cases, the stable-ID\nmigration cost is one `<!-- phase_id: phase_NNN -->` line per phase,\nwith no rewrite of the visible heading.\n\n### 2.6 PLAN.md / ledger directionality\n\n`run_loop`'s success path calls `check_off(active_file, task)` to\nwrite `[x]` to PLAN.md *first*, then calls\n`_ledger_settle(label, TaskOutcome(success=True, ...))` which emits\na `commit_landed` event as audit evidence of what PLAN.md already\nrecords. PLAN.md is the writable surface; the ledger is the\nappend-only witness. Hand-edits flow PLAN.md → ledger, never the\nreverse.\n\n## 3. Architecture\n\n### 3.1 Library placement\n\n```\nbob/\n  bob_tools/\n    ledger/       # already exists; owns events + projected state\n    planfile/     # NEW; owns PLAN.md syntax + canonicalization\n      model.py\n      parser.py\n      renderer.py\n      operations.py\n      fileio.py\n      cli.py\n      tests/\n```\n\nThe two libraries are peers. They cross at exactly two values:\n\n- `phase_id`: written and read by `planfile` via headings and\n  `<!-- phase_id: ... -->` comments; consumed by `ledger` in event\n  payloads.\n- `task_label`: computed by `planfile` from position and stable IDs;\n  resolved to `phase_id` (and, when stable task IDs land, to\n  `task_id`) by the McLoop settle hook.\n\n`mcloop.checklist` becomes a thin compatibility wrapper or\ndisappears once callers migrate. `mcloop.plan_split` and Duplo's\nplanner write through `planfile`.\n\n### 3.2 Function inventory (proposed)\n\nPure operations on typed objects:\n\n```\nparse_plan(text)               -> Plan | PlanSyntaxError\nrender_plan(plan)              -> str\nvalidate_plan(plan)            -> None | PlanValidationError\ncanonicalize(text)             -> str\nmigrate(plan)                  -> Plan\nnext_tasks(plan, limit=1)      -> list[Task]\ncomplete_task(plan, task_id, outcome=None) -> tuple[Plan, tuple[Settlement, ...]]\nfail_task(plan, task_id, reason, outcome=None) -> tuple[Plan, tuple[Settlement, ...]]\nreset_task(plan, task_id)      -> tuple[Plan, tuple[Settlement, ...]]\nadd_task(plan, phase_id, text, deps=(), parent_id=None) -> Plan\nreplace_phase(plan, phase_id, new_phase) -> Plan","numLines":250,"startLine":1,"totalLines":755}}}
