{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01F4v8y9nD6d7CsPMmZptqwZ","type":"tool_result","content":"370\t    indent. If no such ancestor exists in the current phase, fall back\n371\t    to the most recent root task (mcloop's \"orphan\" handling). Returns\n372\t    ``None`` only when both ``stack`` and ``root_tasks`` are empty —\n373\t    i.e. a stray ``[RULEDOUT]`` before any task in the phase, which\n374\t    the caller should drop.\n375\t    \"\"\"\n376\t    for task in reversed(stack):\n377\t        if task.indent_level < indent:\n378\t            return task\n379\t    if root_tasks:\n380\t        return root_tasks[-1]\n381\t    return None\n382\t\n383\t\n384\tdef _attach_deps(\n385\t    indent: int,\n386\t    stack: Sequence[_T],\n387\t) -> tuple[_T | None, bool]:\n388\t    \"\"\"Resolve the task a ``@deps`` sibling line should attach to.\n389\t\n390\t    Walks the open-ancestor stack from innermost (top) to outermost.\n391\t    Returns ``(parent, False)`` for the strict form — first ancestor\n392\t    whose indent is strictly less than the deps line's indent. Returns\n393\t    ``(parent, True)`` for the lenient form — first ancestor at the\n394\t    same indent as the deps line, which callers should report as a\n395\t    validation warning (the deps was not indented under its task).\n396\t    Returns ``(None, False)`` when no candidate exists; the caller\n397\t    should drop the line.\n398\t\n399\t    Unlike ``_attach_ruledout`` there is no root-task fallback: a\n400\t    ``@deps`` line not anchored to a preceding task at lesser-or-equal\n401\t    indent is malformed input rather than an orphan that needs adopting.\n402\t    \"\"\"\n403\t    for task in reversed(stack):\n404\t        if task.indent_level < indent:\n405\t            return task, False\n406\t        if task.indent_level == indent:\n407\t            return task, True\n408\t    return None, False\n409\t\n410\t\n411\tdef _extract_flag_tags(text: str) -> tuple[tuple[str, ...], str]:\n412\t    \"\"\"Strip leading USER/BATCH flag tags from ``text``.\n413\t\n414\t    Per design doc section 4.3, flag tags are recognized only at the\n415\t    leading position. The caller is responsible for stripping the task\n416\t    ID (if any) first. A bracketed flag form appearing later in the\n417\t    text is prose and is left in place.\n418\t    \"\"\"\n419\t    tags: list[str] = []\n420\t    remaining = text\n421\t    while True:\n422\t        m = _FLAG_TAG_RE.match(remaining)\n423\t        if m is None:\n424\t            break\n425\t        tags.append(m.group(1))\n426\t        remaining = remaining[m.end() :].lstrip()\n427\t    return tuple(tags), remaining\n428\t\n429\t\n430\tdef _extract_action_tag(text: str) -> tuple[tuple[str, str] | None, str]:\n431\t    \"\"\"Strip a leading ``[AUTO:<action>] <args>`` tag from ``text``.\n432\t\n433\t    Per design doc section 4.3, the action tag is recognized only at\n434\t    the leading position, after any flag tags. The argument string is\n435\t    the text from the closing bracket to end of line, with the single\n436\t    separating whitespace removed. Non-leading ``[AUTO:...]`` tokens\n437\t    are prose and are left in place.\n438\t\n439\t    Returns ``(None, text)`` when no leading action tag is present;\n440\t    otherwise consumes the rest of the line as the argument string\n441\t    and returns ``((action, args), \"\")``.\n442\t    \"\"\"\n443\t    m = _ACTION_TAG_RE.match(text)\n444\t    if m is None:\n445\t        return None, text\n446\t    action = m.group(1)\n447\t    args = text[m.end() :].lstrip()\n448\t    return (action, args), \"\"\n449\t\n450\t\n451\tdef _extract_annotations(text: str) -> tuple[tuple[tuple[str, str], ...], str]:\n452\t    \"\"\"Strip trailing ``[key: value]`` annotations from ``text``.\n453\t\n454\t    Per design doc sections 4.2 and 4.3, annotations sit at end of line,\n455\t    are bracketed, and are separated from the preceding text by\n456\t    whitespace. Multiple annotations are allowed. Values may contain\n457\t    balanced bracket pairs; this function scans right-to-left with\n458\t    bracket-depth tracking so nested brackets stay inside a single\n459\t    annotation rather than being misparsed as a separate one.\n460\t\n461\t    Annotation keys today are ``feat`` and ``fix``; this extractor\n462\t    accepts any identifier-shaped key. Validation of allowed keys is\n463\t    a separate concern.\n464\t    \"\"\"\n465\t    annotations: list[tuple[str, str]] = []\n466\t    remaining = text\n467\t    while True:\n468\t        rstripped = remaining.rstrip()\n469\t        if not rstripped.endswith(\"]\"):\n470\t            remaining = rstripped\n471\t            break\n472\t        start = _find_matching_open_bracket(rstripped)\n473\t        if start is None:\n474\t            remaining = rstripped\n475\t            break\n476\t        # An annotation must be separated from preceding text by\n477\t        # whitespace (or be at column 0). A `[` abutting a non-WS\n478\t        # character is part of the task text, not an annotation.\n479\t        if start > 0 and not rstripped[start - 1].isspace():\n480\t            remaining = rstripped\n481\t            break\n482\t        content = rstripped[start + 1 : -1]\n483\t        m = _ANNOTATION_CONTENT_RE.match(content)\n484\t        if m is None:\n485\t            remaining = rstripped\n486\t            break\n487\t        annotations.insert(0, (m.group(1), m.group(2)))\n488\t        remaining = rstripped[:start].rstrip()\n489\t    return tuple(annotations), remaining\n490\t\n491\t\n492\tdef _find_matching_open_bracket(s: str) -> int | None:\n493\t    \"\"\"Return the index of the ``[`` matching the final ``]`` in ``s``.\n494\t\n495\t    Walks right-to-left tracking bracket depth so balanced nested\n496\t    brackets inside the candidate annotation are stepped over.\n497\t    Returns ``None`` if ``s`` does not end in ``]`` with a matching\n498\t    opener.\n499\t    \"\"\"\n500\t    if not s.endswith(\"]\"):\n501\t        return None\n502\t    depth = 0\n503\t    for i in range(len(s) - 1, -1, -1):\n504\t        c = s[i]\n505\t        if c == \"]\":\n506\t            depth += 1\n507\t        elif c == \"[\":\n508\t            depth -= 1\n509\t            if depth == 0:\n510\t                return i\n511\t    return None\n512\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c0ad05b9-4ddd-4925-a04d-c46811d784c5","uuid":"cb807592-de9f-4ec1-a4b5-7e744d74f20a","timestamp":"2026-05-16T02:44:19.356Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/mhcoen/proj/bob-tools/bob_tools/planfile/parser.py","content":"    indent. If no such ancestor exists in the current phase, fall back\n    to the most recent root task (mcloop's \"orphan\" handling). Returns\n    ``None`` only when both ``stack`` and ``root_tasks`` are empty —\n    i.e. a stray ``[RULEDOUT]`` before any task in the phase, which\n    the caller should drop.\n    \"\"\"\n    for task in reversed(stack):\n        if task.indent_level < indent:\n            return task\n    if root_tasks:\n        return root_tasks[-1]\n    return None\n\n\ndef _attach_deps(\n    indent: int,\n    stack: Sequence[_T],\n) -> tuple[_T | None, bool]:\n    \"\"\"Resolve the task a ``@deps`` sibling line should attach to.\n\n    Walks the open-ancestor stack from innermost (top) to outermost.\n    Returns ``(parent, False)`` for the strict form — first ancestor\n    whose indent is strictly less than the deps line's indent. Returns\n    ``(parent, True)`` for the lenient form — first ancestor at the\n    same indent as the deps line, which callers should report as a\n    validation warning (the deps was not indented under its task).\n    Returns ``(None, False)`` when no candidate exists; the caller\n    should drop the line.\n\n    Unlike ``_attach_ruledout`` there is no root-task fallback: a\n    ``@deps`` line not anchored to a preceding task at lesser-or-equal\n    indent is malformed input rather than an orphan that needs adopting.\n    \"\"\"\n    for task in reversed(stack):\n        if task.indent_level < indent:\n            return task, False\n        if task.indent_level == indent:\n            return task, True\n    return None, False\n\n\ndef _extract_flag_tags(text: str) -> tuple[tuple[str, ...], str]:\n    \"\"\"Strip leading USER/BATCH flag tags from ``text``.\n\n    Per design doc section 4.3, flag tags are recognized only at the\n    leading position. The caller is responsible for stripping the task\n    ID (if any) first. A bracketed flag form appearing later in the\n    text is prose and is left in place.\n    \"\"\"\n    tags: list[str] = []\n    remaining = text\n    while True:\n        m = _FLAG_TAG_RE.match(remaining)\n        if m is None:\n            break\n        tags.append(m.group(1))\n        remaining = remaining[m.end() :].lstrip()\n    return tuple(tags), remaining\n\n\ndef _extract_action_tag(text: str) -> tuple[tuple[str, str] | None, str]:\n    \"\"\"Strip a leading ``[AUTO:<action>] <args>`` tag from ``text``.\n\n    Per design doc section 4.3, the action tag is recognized only at\n    the leading position, after any flag tags. The argument string is\n    the text from the closing bracket to end of line, with the single\n    separating whitespace removed. Non-leading ``[AUTO:...]`` tokens\n    are prose and are left in place.\n\n    Returns ``(None, text)`` when no leading action tag is present;\n    otherwise consumes the rest of the line as the argument string\n    and returns ``((action, args), \"\")``.\n    \"\"\"\n    m = _ACTION_TAG_RE.match(text)\n    if m is None:\n        return None, text\n    action = m.group(1)\n    args = text[m.end() :].lstrip()\n    return (action, args), \"\"\n\n\ndef _extract_annotations(text: str) -> tuple[tuple[tuple[str, str], ...], str]:\n    \"\"\"Strip trailing ``[key: value]`` annotations from ``text``.\n\n    Per design doc sections 4.2 and 4.3, annotations sit at end of line,\n    are bracketed, and are separated from the preceding text by\n    whitespace. Multiple annotations are allowed. Values may contain\n    balanced bracket pairs; this function scans right-to-left with\n    bracket-depth tracking so nested brackets stay inside a single\n    annotation rather than being misparsed as a separate one.\n\n    Annotation keys today are ``feat`` and ``fix``; this extractor\n    accepts any identifier-shaped key. Validation of allowed keys is\n    a separate concern.\n    \"\"\"\n    annotations: list[tuple[str, str]] = []\n    remaining = text\n    while True:\n        rstripped = remaining.rstrip()\n        if not rstripped.endswith(\"]\"):\n            remaining = rstripped\n            break\n        start = _find_matching_open_bracket(rstripped)\n        if start is None:\n            remaining = rstripped\n            break\n        # An annotation must be separated from preceding text by\n        # whitespace (or be at column 0). A `[` abutting a non-WS\n        # character is part of the task text, not an annotation.\n        if start > 0 and not rstripped[start - 1].isspace():\n            remaining = rstripped\n            break\n        content = rstripped[start + 1 : -1]\n        m = _ANNOTATION_CONTENT_RE.match(content)\n        if m is None:\n            remaining = rstripped\n            break\n        annotations.insert(0, (m.group(1), m.group(2)))\n        remaining = rstripped[:start].rstrip()\n    return tuple(annotations), remaining\n\n\ndef _find_matching_open_bracket(s: str) -> int | None:\n    \"\"\"Return the index of the ``[`` matching the final ``]`` in ``s``.\n\n    Walks right-to-left tracking bracket depth so balanced nested\n    brackets inside the candidate annotation are stepped over.\n    Returns ``None`` if ``s`` does not end in ``]`` with a matching\n    opener.\n    \"\"\"\n    if not s.endswith(\"]\"):\n        return None\n    depth = 0\n    for i in range(len(s) - 1, -1, -1):\n        c = s[i]\n        if c == \"]\":\n            depth += 1\n        elif c == \"[\":\n            depth -= 1\n            if depth == 0:\n                return i\n    return None\n","numLines":143,"startLine":370,"totalLines":512}}}
